Add crypto_sign_publickey() APIThis adds a new API crypto_sign_publickey, which works similarly to thenexisting crypto_sign_keypair() API, but supports a 32-bytenuser-specified seed value (k).nnThis API is necessary for implementing Ed25519 test vectors, fornexample, since we need to pass in a known seed to ensure we'rencomputing the public key correctly.nnThe name and implementation are largely borrowed from Brian Warner'snpython-ed25519 library. See:nnhttps://github.com/warner/python-ed25519/blob/d42d4b7049baf323e7113359f4f6bf88703543bc/src/ed25519.c#L21nnThat said, perhaps a different name would be more descriptive, since itnstill returns a keypair, not just the public key? Or perhaps that'snneedless bikeshedding since this name is already in use.n

crypto_scalarmult_raw()This provides a more direct interface to the crypto_scalarmult function.nBy default, this function includes some bit-twiddling, which, to thenbest of my understanding, ensures the integer provided as the leftnoperand of the multiplication operation fits within a specific limit.n(I believe this limit is the order of NaCl's standard group element,nbut am not entirely certain). This change allows a user to pass innan integer which is not subject to this bit-twiddling and can be passednin wholesale.nnThe reason NaCl provides this API is to intentionally make itneasy-to-use for the purposes of computing public keys from private keysnor for performing Diffie-Hellman. The API it provides now makes itnquite difficult to do anything wrong yet still get a correct answer.nnIf we split this function in half, however, we can expose somenpower-user functionality. Specifically I need this to implementnsemiprivate keys:nnhttps://gist.github.com/tarcieri/4760215nnI've been double checking my implementation against a similar version innSAGE for the past week or so trying to figure out what's wrong, andntoday it was pointed out to me that NaCl's scalar multiplicationnfunction automatically performs bit-twiddling for you.nnI would love to continue to experiment with semiprivate keys on top ofnNaCl. I have no serious intentions of actually using them as part of ancryptosystem until there's some sort of proof of their security, or atnthe very least, some reasonably educated guesses as to its securitynproperties.nnThat said, I would love to have this API. If there's worries aboutnexposing power-user APIs like this, perhaps we can be a bit morenshouty in the API name?nncrypto_scalarmult_dangerously_direct_access() ? ;)n

Add sodium_{malloc,allocarray,free}() and sodium_mprotect_*()ptr = sodium_malloc(size) returns a pointer from which exactly size bytesncan be accessed.nnptr = sodium_allocarray(count, size) allocates enough storage space forncount pointers or scalars of unit size size.nnIn both cases, the region is immediately followed by a guard page.nAs a result, any attempt to access a memory location after ptr[size - 1] willnimmediately trigger a segmentation fault.nnThe allocated region is mlock()ed and filled with 0xd0 bytes.nnA read-only page with the size, a guard page, as well as a canary arenplaced before the returned pointer.nnThe canary is checked by sodium_free(); as a result, altering data rightnbefore ptr is likely to cause sodium_free() to kill the process.nnsodium_free() munlock()s the region and fills it with zeros beforenactually calling free().nnsodium_mprotect_noaccess(), sodium_mprotect_readonly() andnsodium_mprotect_readwrite() can be used to change the protection on the setnof allocated pages.nnReverting the protection to read+write is not required before callingnsodium_free().n

xchacha20poly1305: optimize and be compatible with ietf chacha20poly1305 (#461)Due to SSL, the IETF version of chacha20poly1305 is going to be the onernthat's in libraries places. While the 12-byte nonce thing is a littlernweird, it has other benefits, like adding padding to the auth tag, whichrnmight help fend off certain attacks.rnrnBut more importantly, since chacha20poly1305 in the IETF construction isrnlots of places, it would be useful to be able to build xchacha20poly1305rnout of it. Fortunately it's very easy to make hchacha20 (eitherrnstand-alone, or out of the normal chacha20 block function), and thenrnthat can be composed with an existing library's chacha20poly1305. Itrnlooks a bit like this:rnrnxchacha20poly1305(input, key, nonce) {rnnew_key = hchacha20(key, nonce)rnreturn chacha20poly1305(input, new_key, nonce + 16)rn}rnrnThis is also an efficient way to do it, since it means hchacha20 mustrnonly be computed once.rnrnUnfortuantely, non-IETF xchacha20poly1305 means that you deprivernvirtually all other libraries that only support the more commonrnIETF construction the ability the ability to interoperate withrnlibsodium, through the simple construction. Rather, it forcesrneveryone to reimplement the AEAD part.rnrnSo, this commit adds a xchacha20poly1305 that uses the IETF constructionrnwith the padding.rnrnWhile we're at it, we redefine xchacha20poly1305 in terms ofrnchacha20poly1305, which gives the same output, but computes one lessrnhchacha20 and is generally a lot cleaner and simpler to understand.rnrnSigned-off-by: Jason A. Donenfeld <Jason@zx2c4.com>

Relax most __attribute__ ((nonnull)) to allow 0-length inputs to be NULL.Justifications:n- crypto_(auth|hash|generichash|onetimeauth|shorthash)*:n  it's legal to hash or HMAC a 0-length messagen- crypto_box*: it's legal to encrypt a 0-length messagen- crypto_sign*: it's legal to sign a 0-length messagen- utils:n  comparing two 0-length byte arrays is legaln  memzero on a 0-length byte array is a no-opn  converting an empty hex string to binary results in an empty binary stringn  converting an empty binary string to hex results in an empty hex stringn  converting an empty b64 string to binary results in an empty binary stringn  converting an empty binary string to b64 results in an empty b64 stringn  sodium_add / sodium_sub on zero-length arrays is a no-opnnFor the functions declared in utils.h, I moved the logic into private functions thatnhave the __attribute__ ((nonnull)) check, but they are only called when thencorresponding length argument is non-0. I didn't do this for the hash/box/signnfunctions since it would have been a lot more work and quite a large refactor.n

Optimisation to succeed fast when checking signature scalar is reduced.This provides a minor optimisation for ed25519 signature verification, when usednwithout the -DED25519_COMPAT feature, to strictly check for a fully reducednscalar, `s`, component in variable time by first checking that the mostnsignificant *four* bits are unset, and only if any of them are set proceed tonthe `sc25519_is_canonical` check which performs the full reduction.  This shouldnresult in succeeding fast for the check on roughly half of all well-formed,ncanonicalised signatures.nnThis is safely backwards compatible with the previous implementationnof strict checking for signature scalars.n
